[3] Oregon (Washington County)
Date: Fri 1 Nov 2019
Source: Oregon Live [edited]
https://www.oregonlive.com/health/2019/11/3-tualatin-high-school-students-diagnosed-with-whooping-cough.html


Three cases of whooping cough were discovered at Tualatin High School recently. Those cases add to one at Northeast Portland's Grant High School, where a student was diagnosed with the illness earlier this week.

Washington County has seen 36 confirmed or suspected cases of the illness so far this year [2019], county health department spokeswoman Wendy Gordon told The Oregonian/Oregon Live.

According to the Oregon Health Authority, 93% of Washington County children between the ages of 13 and 17 have received booster shots for whooping cough, also known as pertussis, which also guards against diphtheria and tetanus.

In all of 2018, officials say, Washington County tracked just 24 cases. In 2017, Washington County saw 41 cases, more than twice as many as the 20 that were reported in 2016. Health officials say the up-and-down yearly pattern is typical of the disease. The previous year, 2015, saw a whopping 107 cases of whooping cough in Washington County, a sharp spike over the previous year's 37.

In Multnomah County, health officials have documented 61 suspected or confirmed cases of pertussis since the beginning of the year. Last year [2018], 38 cases had been discovered by Halloween.

There is a vaccine for the disease, which children are required to receive at least 4 times before beginning kindergarten, according to the Oregon Health Authority. Starting at age 7, kids should get at least one booster shot, the agency says.

[Byline: Eder Campuzano]

